# Load shapefile from local path
world = gpd.read_file('data/ne_110m_admin_0_countries/ne_110m_admin_0_countries.shp')

# 2. Sample country values
# data = {
#     'country': ['United States of America', 'China', 'India', 'Brazil', 'Australia'],
#     'value': [100, 200, 150, 80, 120]
# }

highlight_df = pd.DataFrame(total_visits_2024)

# Replacement map for standard country names
replace_map = {
    'Shri Lanka': 'Sri Lanka',
    'UK': 'United Kingdom',
    'USA': 'United States of America',
    'Other': 'Other / Unspecified'  # Optional, if you want to clarify
}

# Apply replacements
highlight_df['Country NRI Belongs To'] = highlight_df['Country NRI Belongs To'].replace(replace_map)
print(highlight_df)


# 3. Merge on correct country column (adjust 'NAME' if your shapefile uses a different one)
world = world.merge(highlight_df, how='left', left_on='NAME', right_on='Country NRI Belongs To')

# 4. Set up colormap
#cmap = mcolors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list("", ["lightgrey", "skyblue"])

# Add a column to define fill color (skyblue for selected, lightgray for rest)
world['fill_color'] = world['total_visits'].apply(lambda x: 'skyblue' if pd.notna(x) else 'lightgrey')


# 5. Plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10))
world.plot(
    ax=ax,
    column='total_visits',
    cmap=cmap,
    missing_kwds={'color': 'lightgrey'},
    edgecolor='white',
    #edgecolor="black",
    alpha=0.5
)

# 6. Add value labels at centroid of each highlighted country
for idx, row in world.dropna(subset=['total_visits']).iterrows():
    if row['geometry'].geom_type == 'Polygon':
        centroid = row['geometry'].centroid
    else:
        centroid = row['geometry'].representative_point()  # safer for multipolygons
        value_in_lakhs = row['total_visits'] / 1e5
        label = f"{row['NAME']}: {value_in_lakhs:.2f} Lakh"
    
    ax.text(
        centroid.x, centroid.y,
        #str(int(row['value'])),
        # f"{row['NAME']}: {int(row['total_visits'])}%",
        f"{row['NAME']}: {value_in_lakhs:.2f} Lakh",
        ha='center',
        fontsize=8,
        color='black'
    )

# 7. Final formatting
plt.title('NRI tourist in 2024')
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

    total_visits_monthwise_2024['visits_lakh'],

    height = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(
        bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2,  # Center of the bar

        f"{height:.2f}",                    # Format: 2 decimal places
        ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=8

import matplotlib.image as mpimg

# Load images
female_img = mpimg.imread('data/female.png')
male_img = mpimg.imread('data/male.png')

# Percentages
female_pct = 43.41
male_pct = 56.59

fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(5, 5))

# Female icon
axs[0].imshow(female_img)
axs[0].axis('off')
axs[0].text(
    female_img.shape[1] / 2,              # X: center width
    female_img.shape[0] / 2,              # Y: center height
    f"{female_pct:.2f}%",
    color='white',
    fontsize=20,
    fontweight='bold',
    ha='center',                         # horizontal align center
    va='center'                          # vertical align center
)
axs[0].set_title('Female')

# Male icon
axs[1].imshow(male_img)
axs[1].axis('off')
axs[1].text(
    male_img.shape[1] / 2,
    male_img.shape[0] / 2,
    f"{male_pct:.2f}%",
    color='white',
    fontsize=20,
    fontweight='bold',
    ha='center',
    va='center'
)
axs[1].set_title('Male')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In[272]:
# Define bins and labels
bins = [0, 24, 44, 64, float('inf')]
labels = ['<25', '25-44', '45-64', '65+']

# Create age group column
df_agewise_2024 = pd.cut(df_2024['Age'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=True)

# Calculate percentages
age_group_pct = (
    df_agewise_2024
    .value_counts(normalize=True)
    .sort_index() * 100
).round(2).reset_index()
age_group_pct.columns = ['Age Group', 'Percentage']

# Horizontal bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))
bars = plt.barh(age_group_pct['Age Group'], age_group_pct['Percentage'], color='gray')

# Add text labels on bars
for bar in bars:
    width = bar.get_width()
    plt.text(width + 1, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height()/2,
             f'{width:.2f}%', va='center', fontsize=10)

plt.xlabel('Percentage')
plt.title('Age Group Distribution of NRI tourist in 2024')
plt.xlim(0, 100)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
#colors = plt.cm.Greys_r(range(100, 100 + len(df)*20, 20))  # greyscale colors
colors = plt.cm.Set3(range(len(total_visits_citywise_2024)))  # Adjust for the number of categories

# Create pie chart with a hole
wedges, texts, autotexts = plt.pie(
    total_visits_citywise_2024['percentage'],
    labels=total_visits_citywise_2024['City Stayed'],
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    startangle=90,
    #radius=0.5, 
    colors=colors,
    wedgeprops={'width': 0.3}  # This makes it a donut
)

# Center title
plt.title('City-wise Distribution of NRI Tourist Stays (2024)', fontsize=14)
plt.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio makes the pie a circle

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

total_visits_hotelwise_2024 = df_2024.groupby(['India Hotel Name']).size().reset_index(name='total_visits')

# Sort by city ascending
total_visits_hotelwise_2024 = total_visits_hotelwise_2024.sort_values('India Hotel Name')

# Convert total_visits to lakhs
#total_visits_citywise_2024['visits_lakh'] = total_visits_citywise_2024['total_visits'] / 1e5  # 1 lakh = 100,000

# print(total_visits_citywise_2024)

# Calculate percentage

# Format to 2 decimal places (optional)

import squarify  # for treemap


# Treemap plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))

# Define labels with name and %
labels = [
    f"{name}\n{pct:.2f}%" for name, pct in zip(total_visits_hotelwise_2024['India Hotel Name'], total_visits_hotelwise_2024['percentage'])
]

# Plot using 'percentage' or 'total_visits' as size
squarify.plot(
    sizes=total_visits_hotelwise_2024['percentage'],
    label=labels,
    color=plt.cm.Set3.colors[:len(total_visits_hotelwise_2024)],
    alpha=0.8,
    text_kwargs={'fontsize': 10}
)

plt.axis('off')
plt.title('Treemap chart of Hotel Preferences by NRI Tourists in India (2024)', fontsize=14)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
